LibGDX version used 1.0.1

I have been using MotionState for synchronizing Visual/Physical transform and rotation sets upon simple Model and Rigid bodies. This has been working great, until I need to implement scale.

The docs [here](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/wiki/Bullet-physics) state:

> Keep in mind that Bullet's transformation only supports translation (location) and rotation (orientation). Any other transformation, like scaling, is not supported.

But that is not necessarily true, you are just not supposed to scale the RigidBody itself.  The [Bullet doc](https://code.google.com/p/bullet/source/browse/trunk/Bullet_User_Manual.pdf) for version 2.82 (which I am not sure what version libgdx has included). On page 25, under the "Static, Dynamic and Kinematic Rigid Bodies" section you will read:

> This world transform has to be a rigid body transform, which means it should contain no scaling, shear etc. If you want an object to be scaled, you can scale the collision shape.

Scaling a RigidBody via MotionState ModelInstance transform will "run", and it does produce a smaller physical object. But this object is now broken, it sporadically will collide with other objects, but the collisions will be incorrect, most of the time objects will pass right through.

My solution was to use the ModelInstance transform for rotation and orientation, and to only scale the ModelInstances nodes. Example code snippet from my ModelInstance extended class:

```
public void applyScale(Vector3 scale){

        //If scaling smaller than zero, physics break.
        // So here we prevent that.
        if(scale.x <= 0
        || scale.y <= 0
        || scale.z <= 0) {
            return;
        }

        //We store the scale as a convenience when getScale is called
        this.scale = scale;

        //Apply the scaling to all nodes under this ModelInstance, but not this.transform.
        for (Node node : nodes) {
            node.scale.set(scale);
        }
        calculateTransforms();

        //Now we apply the scaling to the Collision Shape Locally
        body.getCollisionShape().setLocalScaling(scale);

    }
```

Whereas my transforms and rotations do modify the ModelInstance transform directly:

```
public void applyRotation(Quaternion rotation){
        transform.set(
            rotation.x,
            rotation.y,
            rotation.z,
            rotation.w
        );
    }
```

This is working, but feels a bit "hack-ish". It would be ideal if there was a way/abstraction to apply scale to the transform that is shared between ModelInstance and a Bullet bodys MotionState without causing major inefficiencies. Alas, at am at a loss for a better solution than what I have provided.

If there is a clear suggestion/answer with a better approach, I would love to hear it. Otherwise if the code snippet can be used in core libgdx or even in the docs to assist others, all the better.

Thanks!
